Sure hope Ed doesn't take the test, the last test we gave to pilots at Camp Pendelton in 69 was the National Emergency Test, where the announcer said, If this had been an actual emergency, you would have,.... of course they all failed. <br>
Stats are great resources; I remember working Wilshire Division and one year we had one fatality from a three-car traffic pile up. The following year an elderly gentlemen suffered a heart attack and killed himself and his two passengers in a one car traffic accident. The following week we were told that since fatalities in the division were up 300%, we were suppose to cite more people for traffic violations and the motor squad would be working the division for the next two years to try and bring down the fatal accident rate. <br><br>
Tom,<br>
I would venture to say that a good percentage of the citizens living in San Diego are associated with individuals that served in the military in one way or another. The same holds true for San Clemente or any other military town. So 40% of the homeless in San Diego being vets maybe close to the truth, however, I have a brother that works at the largest homeless shelter in San Diego and I can tell you that 70-80% of the individuals he comes in contact there and the individuals that I have seen when I have visited him are not veterans. A great many of them are younger then 40 years of age and never served in the military. Many of the older homeless individuals there have some type of military background because they worked in industry that supplied military hardware or other military services that closed down in recent years. That may have something to do with it.<br>
Our church feeds about three hundred families in Riverside every Christmas, at least a couple of dozen are homeless yet in the seven years we have been doing it I can remember the individuals that were vets but that's in Riverside. In another area near the air base the homeless vet rate is higher, and that's understandable. Guess stats don't tell us much, it all has to do with who said it and why and that makes all the difference. What is true in San Diego may not be true elsewhere and that's the problem with quoting things that pertain to Vets or labeling 40% of the homeless as vets because of what maybe true in San Diego, because it soon spreads as gospel truth and we'll see it quoted on the Six O'clock news before too long. Its just another negative we have to content with regarding the Vietnam war, perhaps that why, I see red, when I see info like that posted, because of my background investigating a lot of misinformation that was published about Vietnam by the anti-war protestors who had other motives then just protesting the war, but that's for another time.<br><br>

